{{Infobox Cloud |name=Cirrus intortus |image location= |image name= |abbreviation=Ci in |symbol=CH_1.png |genus=Cirrus (''curl of hair'') |species= |variety=intortus (''interlaced'') |altitude_m=Above 5,000 |altitude_ft=Above 16,500 |appearance=tangled, interlaced<ref>{{cite web |title=Cirrus |url=http://www.clouds-online.com/cloud_atlas/cirrus/cirrus.htm |work=Cloud Atlas |accessdate=13 July 2011 |author=Wolken Online}}</ref> |precipitation=No}} '''Cirrus intortus''' is a variety of [[cirrus cloud]]. The name ''cirrus intortus'' is derived from [[Latin]], meaning "twisted, wound".<ref>{{cite web |title=Definition of intortus |url=http://latinlexicon.org/definition.php?p1=2030263 |accessdate=13 July 2011 |author=Numen - The Latin Lexicon}}</ref> The variety of intortus clouds is specific to cirrus clouds, and they appear as interwound strands of cirrus clouds with a purely random pattern.<ref>{{cite book |last=Dunlop |first=Storm |title=The weather identification handbook |year=2003 |publisher=Lyons Press |location=Guilford, Conn. |isbn=1-58574-857-9 |pages=58 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=BR2ft4G5TgQC&lpg=PA1&pg=PA58#v=onepage&q=intortus&f=false |edition=1st Lyons Press |accessdate=13 July 2011}}</ref> The filaments are often curved in a very irregular pattern.<ref>{{cite web |last=Callanan |first=Martin |title=Cirrus intortus |url=http://nephology.eu/cirrus/cirrus-intortus |work=International Cloud Atlas |publisher=nephology.eu |accessdate=13 July 2011}}</ref>
Like other [[cirrus cloud]]s, cirrus intortus occur at high [[altitude]]s.<ref>{{cite web |title=Cirrus intortus (Ci in) |url=http://www.theweatherobserver.com/?p=71 |accessdate=13 July 2011 |author=The Weather Observer |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120327014354/http://www.theweatherobserver.com/?p=71 |archivedate=27 March 2012 |df= }}</ref>
